<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-11-05T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-11-05T16:00:00-05:00" n="133" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d133">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A3/1886a: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-11-05T16:00:00-05:00">November
                                    5, 1936—4 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>139. You are requested to present to the Japanese Government a memorandum
                            stating that this Government has decided to exercise its right under
                            Article 17 of the London Naval Treaty, 1930, to retain 19,000 tons of
                            destroyers in view of the fact that on December 31, 1936, we will have
                            only 75,900 tons of completed cruisers of sub-category (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>), that is to say 67,600 less than the tonnage
                            which is permitted under the terms of the 1930 Naval Treaty in this
                            sub-category.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>